releases/0/tender/title: Rough Sleeper Outreach Service
releases/0/tender/description:
Reading Borough Council requires a provider to deliver a service to households, across tenure type, to intervene early in preventing homelessness and sustaining tenancies.

The service will deliver:

• Early upstream homelessness prevention support to clients who are threatened with homelessness, or who may be threatened with homelessness in the future if their immediate support needs are not addressed, by leading on a No First Night Out (NFNO) initiative in Reading.

• Support to the Council in delivering its duties, powers and obligations towards people who are homeless or at risk of homelessness under the Homelessness Reduction Act 2017.

• A two tier service that includes Tier 1: Drop-in and triage; Tier 2: Shorter and longer term support planning and resettlement support to provide the most appropriate level and length of intervention/support to each client.

• Shorter term support plans over a three to six month period where more than brief intervention(s) is required.

• Longer term support plans, as agreed with the Commissioner, where more than brief intervention(s) or shorter term support is required.

Additional information: Organisations interested in expressing an interest in this procurement should download the procurement documents which are available on the Council'[input]s e-tendering system at: https://in-tendhost.co.uk/readingbc/aspx/Home and complete as instructed.

The Portal is free of charge - to register please follow the supplier registration guidance which is available on the Portal. Contractors wishing to be considered for this tendering opportunity must complete the tender documents and return them electronically via the Council's e-tendering portal.

Please note: you must register your interest via the Council's e-tendering portal if you intend to submit a tender. Interested parties must log onto the Council's e-tendering portal at: https://in-tendhost.co.uk/readingbc, to express an interest and download the procurement documents. All communications regarding this procurement exercise will be conducted through the Council's e-tendering portal including requests for clarifications or general enquiries. The procurement documents will be available for download up until the closing time and date for tender submissions, it is the organisation's responsibility to ensure that they download the documents in ample time to ensure that they can be completed and returned electronically, along with supporting documents, prior to the closing time and date stipulated. Before completing the tender, potential providers/suppliers should ensure that the e-mail address that has been used to register their organisation will be checked regularly as the Council's e-tendering system will generate automatic notifications to this e-mail address when there are updates, changes or messages sent relating to the project. Potential bidders should also check that their organisation's details are correct and kept up to date.

Technical questions and assistance regarding the use and operation of the Portal should be addressed to the In-Tend Help Desk - e-mail: support@in-tend.co.uk , telephone number +44 8442728810.

releases/0/tender/title: Morley Memorial Primary School Cleaning tender
releases/0/tender/description: Morley Memorial is a Community primary school in the district of Cambridgeshire.  The school is named after Samuel Morley who was a benefactor of the Homerton Teacher Training College and a member of the Congregational board of Education.  The school was founded at the end of the 19th century as a practice school for the College. It is one of the oldest non-denominational schools in Cambridge, having celebrated its centenary in 2000.The school is situated near the centre of the city, on the south side. The population of the area is diverse: some families have lived for generations within the community, others are more recently settled and others are here only for a short time connected to periods of work or study.  Many of this last group come from outside the UK and the school has a number of children for whom English is an additional language.

releases/0/tender/title: 1718-0377 Summerversity, Launchpad and/or Summer Weekend Offer 2018
releases/0/tender/description:
Islington Council is seeking providers or consortia of providers to submit proposals for the Summerversity, Launchpad and/or Summer Weekend Offer which will be delivered over the summer holidays primarily in August 2018. The programme will offer a wide range of free social, recreational and educational activities for young people aged 13 -24 providing opportunities for formal accreditation where appropriate. The aim of the programme is to engage young people in a range of stimulating courses and activities over their summer holiday that will develop their skills and interests, raise their ambitions and aspirations and expose them to the new experiences and opportunities. The maximum total value of this contract is £160,000 over the maximum four month term of the contract. The funding will be allocated for the Summerversity, Launchpad and/or Summer Weekend Offer 2018 across four themes. The council is looking to award up to ten contracts in each theme (subject to meeting minimum standards) .  The contract will run for a period of four months from June 2018 till September 2018 including evaluation of the programme. For more information on this opportunity please visit the London Tenders Portal https://procontract.due-north.com/register
You must contact isyp@islington.gov.uk for copy of quotation documents. Any questions relating to this exercise must be emailed to the above address. Completed quotations should be returned to isyp@islington.gov.uk by 12 noon on 28 March 2018.
Please be aware that we will not accept any late submissions.

To provide new storage facility for Field Operations plant & equipment, tools and PPE, by providing a new steel framed metal clad storage building on a clear area of the existing Environment Agency Trentside Nottingham site (NG2 5FA). 
 The works comprise of supply & construction of a steel framed storage building including foundations/ground works, drainage works, building construction, electrical works, internal & external finished surfaces. The Contractor shall manage all stages of the project including the sourcing/procuring of the plant/equipment/materials, all construction works, the submission/inspection/sign-off of the building regulations, and the site management of the overall project.

Additional information: Please note that the Environment Agency now use an eSourcing portal called Bravo.  If you wish to express an interest in any opportunities please visit the website https://defra.bravosolution.co.uk/web/login.html .

Phone: 0800 368 4850

releases/0/tender/description:
De Montfort University seeks to engage a suitably qualified and experienced Contractor to carry out the service and inspection of Water Management Systems and Legionella Control on its Leicester Campus and associated sites.
      
      The Contractor will provide Planned Preventative Maintenance and a reactive callout service to all hot and cold water storage and delivery systems located in De Montfort University buildings (as per the asset list in D3 Specifications) and in accordance with requirements of the most recent Legionella risk assessment and as set out in SFG20, HSE Approved Document ACOPL8, HSG274 and BS6700 and all other best practices.
      
      The contract is for 2 years, with additional extension years of 1yr+, 1yr+ (total 4 years).
      The extension period will depend upon successful delivery performance, contract management, meeting all KPI's and the satisfaction of DMU. It will be part of JCT Measured term Contract.

releases/0/tender/title: Provision of School Meals for East Ward Community Primary and Higher Lane Primary
releases/0/tender/description:
East Ward Community Primary School and Higher Lane Primary School are seeking to appoint a suitably qualified and experienced company to undertake their school meals catering provision. The successful company will be required to provide healthy balanced meals in line with recognised guidelines ensuring choice, dietary needs and tastes are met. Menus will need to be varied and rotated on a regular basis.

Bidders will need to be able to demonstrate that their solution provides the facility for an end to end electronic ordering process incorporating the ability to order from multiple settings e.g. in school or at home. Provide an online payment system for the collection of payments from parents. Pricing will be per meal. Full details of requirements are contained within the tender documentation.

It is anticipated that the new arrangement will commence from Monday 16th April 2018. School closes for Easter on Thursday 29th March 2018 and will reopen on Monday 16th April 2018. The successful bidder will be given access to school, during the Easter holiday period, in order for school meals to be offered from Monday 16th April 2018.

releases/0/tender/title: Provision of a Level 5 Qualification in Data Analytics
releases/0/tender/description:
The Contracting Body is seeking to establish Contracts with multiple Suppliers to deliver an educational programme offering a variety of learning options and a Level 5 qualification in Data Analytics for Government.
The Contract will cover all aspects of the academic content required to complete a level 5 qualification. The Contract will be available to all Public-Sector bodies in the UK.
https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations
The Contracting Body will hold a list of Preferred Suppliers. The qualification, and related modules for continuous professional development, will be available for all members of the Government Statistical Service which includes Civil Servants in the main analytical professions and those aspiring to join these. These staff are based across the UK with hubs in Hampshire, London, South Wales, Leeds/Manchester/Sheffield, Glasgow, and Belfast.
Other new continuous professional development courses are proving very popular, with over 40 learners attending the MSc module. Historically, similar courses have attracted 20 or more learners per module. The workforce is transforming and there is a high appetite for training and building capability.
The Contract will commence for the Academic Year 2018/2019 and run for a period of five years. Any student commencing their programme before the Contract expiry will remain with their Preferred Supplier for the duration of their individual programme. Within the Contract students will also be able to access individual modules where they do not wish to complete a full qualification programme, Suppliers may offer different credit accumulator programmes.
Each prospective student and their line manager will have full discretion regarding the selection of a Supplier, based on the location, learning routes, and available optional modules. Suppliers will be required to attend Annual Strategic Review meetings and Quarterly Service Review meetings, where the course content, students' progress, and other issues will be discussed to ensure the contract and available module content remains relevant to the needs of Government and the wider public sector.
In the longer term, the Contracting Body are keen to
a) improve continuity between internal & external courses & programmes;
b) create an integrated knowledge and learning framework which is essentially a continuum of learning from basic through to advanced knowledge;
c) both recognise and reinforce an individual's prior knowledge and skills;
d) grow a framework of Suppliers able, together, to deliver across the UK.
The programme must be ready to run no later than the end of September 2018, with prospective students being able to enroll from April 2018 onwards.

releases/0/tender/title: Bikeability - National Standard Cycle Training Scheme
releases/0/tender/description:
The purpose of this tender is to seek a provider to deliver bicycle training to children of school age in accordance with the 'Bikeability - National Standard Cycle Training Scheme' and Wigan Council's tender documentation.

Wigan Council currently has a strong offer relating to cycling which is intended to carry cycling culture through residents early years and into adulthood. Via the Greater Manchester Combined Authority (GMCA) grant, the Council administers free bike hire, free Dr Bike sessions, free adult and family cycling activities, free Cycling Challenge projects for employees and grants for schools and businesses towards the cost of new cycle parking. The Council also partners with Inspiring Healthy Lifestyles who run community cycling initiatives and the 'On ya bike' project across the borough. Bikeability is a key part of our cycling offer and is intended to nurture cycling at a young age. 

Bikeability training is wholly grant funded on an annual basis by the Department for Transport (DfT). For the financial years 2018/19 - 2019/20 our grant eligibility will allow us to fund 3,887 training places.

Training must be delivered to the Bikeability standard set out by the DfT. The training must be delivered via Bikeability accredited instructors trained to the National Cycle Training Standard. More details can be found at http://bikeability.dft.gov.uk/. Interested applicants are directed to the Invitation to Tender documentation which contains full details and a specification with regard to the delivery of this service.

The proposed contract will be for an initial period from 1 April 2018 to 31 March 2019, with a further optional extension for the period covering April 2019 to March 2020 (subject to central Government funding as well as successful performance).

The deadline for the return of final tender bids is Friday 9th March 2018 at 12:00 noon.

releases/0/tender/title: Provision of Corporate Banking Services
releases/0/tender/description:
The University of Southampton has a requirement for the provision of Corporate Banking and Merchant Card services.  The University requires a banking service which will include the provision and maintenance of bank accounts, income handling (including cash and cheques), a full range of payment processing options (including electronic bank transfer, both domestic and international, BACS and direct debit) and other services associated with higher education banking arrangements, including an electronic banking platform for payment initiation and balance/transaction reporting. The University also requires the provision of Merchant Card services to support a full range of card payment options (to include virtual terminal payments, recurring card payments, web payments, DCC payments) through a variety of payment solutions (including contactless, chip and pin, wireless and mobile).  Merchant Card services provision would need to support the University's PCI DSS requirements and offer a suitable management information system for reporting purposes.
      
      The University of Southampton is seeking to develop efficient and cost-effective banking arrangements which will be capable of meeting future market and technological changes, and which will meet, and often exceed, user expectations.  It is looking to build relationships with organisation/s in which it can be confident to deliver tangible value to the University.

releases/0/tender/title: UK SBS RE17237 Aeromagnetic sensor, associated data acquisition system and altitude compensation software
releases/0/tender/description:
The final date and time for the submission of bids is Monday 10th July 2017 at 14:00

Note : Please disregard any content in this notice that requests your organisation "to apply directly to the buyer" as this unfortunately a system generated error, that is outside of the Contracting Authorities control .

All tender information must be submitted through the CCS eSourcing Portal.

Aeromagnetic sensor, associated data acquisition system and attitude compensation software

The British Antarctic Survey is seeking to purchase an aeromagnetic sensor, associated data acquisition system and attitude compensation software suitable for operation in an unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV). The platform has an optimal payload of 10kg. For geophysics we aim to operate magnetic and other sensors simultaneously.

The UAV platform will supply the magnetic data acquisition system with DC power (5, 12, or 24V), and optionally a NMEA GPS data stream, 1pps timing pulse, GPS antenna feed, x,y,z data feed from a three axis magnetometer (TFM100-G2), and lidar altimeter data. The platform will be operating in Antarctica from remote field camps for extended missions lasting up to 14 hours. The overall magnetic system must therefore be rugged, reliable and easy to use.

The full detailed specification can be found in the attached RE17237 Aeromagnetic sensor  ITQ Invitation to Quote document.

How to Apply

As part of the strategic alliance between UK Shared Business Services Ltd (UK SBS) and Crown Commercial Service (CCS), UK SBS will be using the CCS eSourcing Suite for this procurement.

To register on the CCS eSourcing portal please follow the details contained within the Additional Information section of this notice.

If you are already registered on the CCS eSourcing portal and wish to register your interest in this opportunity please email; expressionofinterest@crowncommercial.gov.uk. 

Your email must clearly state: 
•             the name and reference for the procurement you wish to register for; 
•             the name of the registered Bidder; 
•             the name and contact details for the registered individual sending the email.

Additional information: DO NOT APPLY DIRECTLY TO BUYER

All submissions will be assessed in accordance with the Public Contracts Regulations 2015, for procurement values that exceed Regulation 5 (Threshold amounts) 
 
Responses must be received by the date in the bid documents.

Responses received outside or concurrently using the eSourcing process will not be accepted or considered further for this opportunity.

How to Register on the CCS eSourcing Suite

Full details of this opportunity can be found on the e-sourcing portal please follow instructions below. If you have not yet registered on the eSourcing Suite, this can be done online at https://gpsesourcing.cabinetoffice.gov.uk by following the link 'Register for CCS eSourcing'. 

Please note that, to register, you must have a valid DUNS number (as provided by Dun and Bradstreet) for the organisation which you are registering, who will be entering into a contract if invited to do so. 

Once you have registered on the eSourcing Suite, a registered user can express an interest for a specific procurement. This is done by emailing expressionofinterest@crowncommercial.gov.uk. 

Your email must clearly state: 
•             name and reference for the procurement you wish to register for; 
•             name of the registered Bidder; 
•             name and contact details for the registered individual sending the email. 

Crown Commercial Service will process the email and then enable the Bidder to access the procurement online via the e-Sourcing Suite. The registered user will receive a notification email to alert them once this has been done. The Sourcing documents can then be accessed on the eSourcing Suite at: https://gpsesourcing.cabinetoffice.gov.uk using the instructions detailed in the Specification documents within Contracts Finder. 

As a user of the e-Sourcing Suite you will have access to Emptoris email messaging service which facilitates all messages sent to you and from you in relation to any specific RFX event. 

Please note it is your responsibility to access these emails on a regular basis to ensure you have sight of all relevant information. 

For technical assistance on use of the e-Sourcing Suite please contact Crown Commercial Service Helpdesk: Telephone: 0345 010 3503 

Training documents to support Bidders to utilise Emptoris CCS eSourcing are available in the Contracts Finder Tender documents section.

Our broad range of expert services is shared by our customers. This allows our customers the freedom to focus resources on core activities; innovating and transforming their own organisations.

releases/0/tender/title: Provision of a Level 3 Qualification in Data Analytics
releases/0/tender/description:
The Contracting Body is seeking to establish Contracts with multiple Suppliers to deliver an educational programme offering a variety of learning options and a Level 3 qualification in Data Analytics for Government. 

The Contract will cover all aspects of the academic content required to complete a level 3 qualification. The Contract will be available to all Public-Sector bodies in the UK. 

https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations

The Contracting Body will hold a list of Preferred Suppliers. The qualification, and related modules for continuous professional development, will be available for all members of the Government Statistical Service which includes Civil Servants in the main analytical professions and those aspiring to join these. These staff are based across the UK with hubs in Hampshire, London, South Wales, Leeds/Manchester/Sheffield, Glasgow, and Belfast.
Initially there will be a focus on building capability within the Operational Delivery Profession in the Office for National Statistics, based in Newport, South Wales, and Titchfield, Hampshire, but the areas above are also required.

Other new continuous professional development courses are proving very popular, with over 40 learners attending a  recent MSc module. Historically, similar courses have attracted 20 or more learners per module. The workforce is transforming and there is a high appetite for training and building capability so we anticipate that the demand will grow rapidly with the introduction of more innovative learning solutions.

The Contract will commence for the Academic Year 2018/2019 and run for a period of five years. Any student commencing their programme before the Contract expiry will remain with their Preferred Supplier for the duration of their individual programme. Within the Contract students will also be able to access individual modules where they do not wish to complete a full qualification programme, Suppliers may offer different credit accumulator programmes. 

Each prospective student and their line manager will have full discretion regarding the selection of a Supplier, based on the location, learning routes, and available optional modules. Suppliers will be required to attend Annual Strategic Review meetings and Quarterly Service Review meetings, where the course content, students' progress, and other issues will be discussed to ensure the contract and available module content remains relevant to the needs of Government and the wider public sector.

In the longer term, the Contracting Body are keen to 
a) improve continuity between internal & external courses & programmes; 
b) create an integrated knowledge and learning framework which is essentially a continuum of learning from basic through to advanced knowledge; 
c) both recognise and reinforce an individual's prior knowledge and skills;
d) grow a framework of Suppliers able, together, to deliver across the UK.
 
The programme must be ready to run no later than the end of September 2018

Additional information: Here is a link to the opportunity on our e-tendering tool

https://in-tendhost.co.uk/ons/aspx/ProjectManage/453

releases/0/tender/title: South West Region of Readers App
releases/0/tender/description:
The positive impact and outcomes of reading and creativity are wide-ranging and known to support health, wellbeing, intellectual, personal and social development.  

The innovative Region of Readers project is about reading for pleasure and wellbeing and is taking place in geographic areas of regeneration. The project involves six library services in South West England in partnership with Literature Works (the literature development agency for the region), The Reader (a charity running shared reading groups) and SWRLS (the South Western Regional Library Service).  The project aims to support reader development through curated literature resources and engaging communities in shared reading activities, creating cultural content, and cultural events. The project is funded by an Arts Council England grant as part of the Libraries Opportunities for Everyone Innovation Fund programme.

The digital app is one of three main project strands. It will provide people with ways into reading and into the other two project strands, which are the shared reading groups and cultural activities. It will also help promote improved literacy, reading for pleasure and increased digital skills. 

The app builds on the strong track record of the South West Reading Passport, an annual print booklet promoted by South West libraries, featuring a different themed and curated reading list each year.  This year, that content will be delivered in app form for the first time.  
The Region of Readers web pages, currently hosted on the Literature Works website, will sit alongside the app.

We are looking for a fun, accessible and attractive approach to developing our app.  We want it to appeal to the widest possible range of potential readers, rich with interactive content, easy to use and easy for project partners to populate.

releases/0/tender/title: Staffordshire Healthy Communities Service
releases/0/tender/description:
Staffordshire County Council (SCC) wishes to transform its health improvement and lifestyle commissioning model to reduce demand and the flow of Staffordshire citizens into Health and Social Care provision. This will require a focus on maintaining an active and healthy population whilst providing appropriate support to individuals who are over 50 years old, in communities which have the poorest health and are at greatest risk of requiring Health and Social Care.
The Healthy Communities Service will need to build on local assets and skills within the community to help citizens help themselves and one another and connect individuals to wider community networks and programmes.
The Healthy Communities Service will:
•	Deliver assessment/referral training to a wide-range of frontline workers / health professionals. 
•	Provide NHS Health Checks in targeted areas.
•	Provide behavioural intervention to individuals  (50+) from targeted areas and to those identified by risk assessment tools to reduce preventable risk factors that result in poor health e.g. stopping smoking, improving poor diets, increasing physical activity levels and social prescribing aimed at reducing loneliness and social isolation.
•	Provide bespoke targeted support to individuals who are showing signs of struggling to cope, agreeing support required using an asset-based approach and providing personalised coaching and practical skills to promote independence and resilience e.g. malnutrition and dehydration prevention, home-based activity to increase mobility and ability to maintain activities of daily living, social prescribing and befriending.

releases/0/tender/title: International Best Practice Guide to Equality on Sexual Orientation and Gender Identity
releases/0/tender/description: See 'Attachments' for full description.  The Government Equalities Office are seeking the development of a guide which aims to share international best practice on equality with regard to protecting against discrimination on the grounds of sexual orientation, gender identity or expression and sex characteristics. Although 36 out of 52 Commonwealth member states criminalise homosexuality, there has been progress in some parts of the Commonwealth, such as Nauru, Seychelles and Mozambique decriminalising same sex acts in the last couple of years. But positive achievements go beyond decriminalisation of same sex acts and a number of countries have laws protecting against discrimination in employment, allow organisations working on these issues to register, and/or have other inclusive policies. Celebrating and sharing these positive steps is vital in order to ensure this progress continues. The upcoming Commonwealth Summit presents an opportunity to engage with Commonwealth member states and continue the UK's special responsibility to advance equality across the Commonwealth for people with minority sexual orientations and gender identities.

releases/0/tender/title: I-Venture
releases/0/tender/description:
In 2012 a group of key stakeholders came together to develop 'Namibia Bound' - a unique 18 month programme providing young people from Bolsover district the opportunity of a lifetime. Working with six secondary schools, thirty students (plus six reserves) were selected to participate in a challenging programme of personal development culminating in a two-week expedition in Namibia under canvass without luxuries.  The students selected had a variety of barriers to progressing positively at post-16 and had to abide by a strict code of conduct for the entirety of the project. As well as being Ambassadors for the area, along with their families, had to fundraise a significant amount of money to secure a place. The key stakeholders involved included Bolsover Partnership, Hardwick Clinical Commissioning Group, six secondary schools, Raising Aspirations project and a leading expedition provider, all working to ensure the success of the programme. 

To secure their position, students are required to apply, attend interview (parents and carers also interviewed), be provided with a conditional offer, raise £1500 towards the costs, abide by a strict code of conduct, remain fully committed to the project and attend minimum weekly meetings with their in-school lead, pass their risk assessment and attend the mandatory training weekend.  Their position can be lost at any time during this process and further to this the conduct of their wider family can also jeopardise their place. 

Following the initial project in 2014, Namibia Bound 2016 has provided a further 30 students with the opportunity to work in a residential school to deliver lifesaving first aid training to the local community and undertake a trek in the Namib desert.
Due to the impact this is having for communities in Bolsover, we are now aiming for an October 2019 expedition with the project commencing in April 2018.  For further information, please visit http://raisingaspirations.weebly.com/namibia-bound.html

releases/0/tender/title: Development of a Cross Platform Mobile Application
releases/0/tender/description:
Westcountry Rivers Trust (WRT) is inviting tenders for the development in two phases of a cross-platform mobile application (IOS and Android) to improve and update their 18 year old fishing access scheme, Westcountry Angling Passport

What the WAPapp needs to achieve...

The current passport scheme runs entirely on a paper counterfoil system, with anglers buying books of 10 tokens valued at £3 each. Anything from two to five tokens need to be filled out with personal details and posted in the a letter box at the start of the beat (beatbox) before fishing.A catch return stating the angler's success or lack thereof is then posted at the end of their session.
This allows anglers to decide whether to fish at the last minute and get in the water seconds later. However from the Trust's point of view it requires a large investment of effort to collect, sort and count the 1000s of individual paper tokens and properly account for them at the end of the year. With most WAP funds going directly to the beat owners, the more anglers we host in the Westcountry, the more costly to the trust the current scheme becomes.
The app will therefore:
•	Reduce the workload of WRT staff and volunteers in collection and counting of tokens;
•	Work in partnership with the current paper system;
•	Appeal to and attract the next generation of anglers;
•	Promote the local services and facilities that Cornwall has to offer the visiting angler (It is estimated that each visit by an angler contributes £175 to the local economy through spending on food, accommodation, tackle and transport);
•	Lower the barrier to entry for those new to the eccentricities of river game fishing.

Additional information: Please read the attached Invitation to tender in full before requesting further information or documents.
WRT's procurement policy adheres to the EU Treaty Principles and the National Rules. It also incorporates a number of principles that we believe demonstrate our commitment to fulfilling our charitable objectives and ensuring the fairness and integrity of our procurement practices:
•	Demonstrating 'best value for money'.
•	Environmental considerations.
•	Minimising the risk to WRT in terms of liability.
WRT will make use of an NEC3 Profesional Services Short Contract (PSSC) to best facilitate the responsibilities and duties of us and the successful developer. A break clause will be included in the event that development and deployment of Phase One completion is not met satisfactorily.
All intellectual property rights in this ITT and all material provided by WRT to applicants relating to this ITT are and shall remain the property of WRT.

releases/0/tender/title: Specialist Leisure Consultant
releases/0/tender/description:
Chiltern District Council's vision is to: 
Provide accessible, affordable, sustainable and high quality leisure facilities that meet the future needs of residents, enabling them to lead active and healthy lifestyles
One of the key challenges to help achieve the Council's vision is to replace its largest leisure centre, Chiltern Pools in Amersham which is coming to the end of its operational life. The existing operator contract is scheduled to come to an end in March 2020. To identify and address future needs the Council undertook a sports facility and leisure needs assessment in 2015 that highlighted a clear need to replace Chiltern Pools Leisure Centre in order to meet the future needs of Chilterns residents. www.chiltern.gov.uk/background 

The Council has also undertaken a public consultation to gauge residents' appetite for developing a new leisure centre facility. The results demonstrated overwhelming support to take the project forward www.chiltern.gov.uk/consultationresults including bringing the surrounding community facilities (library, nursery and community halls) into one building. The ultimate aim is to create a new state of the art leisure/community hub facility that will serve the needs of residents for the next thirty years and beyond. www.chiltern.gov.uk/chilternpoolsredevelopment   

Looking Forward
Following the completion of the leisure needs assessment and community consultation the Council wishes to move the project forward and is now seeking to appoint a specialist leisure consultant to:
	develop an outcome based leisure operator contract to tender the operation of the current and proposed facilities
	support the procurement process from the point of soft market testing through to the appointment of an operator to deliver the outcome based contract from 1st April 2020

Closing date for submissions is 12 noon on 19th March 2018, please contact Paul Nanji, Principal Leisure and Wellbeing Manager at LHunter@chiltern.gov.uk for further information.

The provider must be fully operational by 2nd August 2018. This procurement is being carried out by NHS SCW Commissioning Support on behalf of the Commissioners.
This Notice as a call for competition is initially published as a notice for expressions of interest. The Commissioner may then choose to proceed to publish tender documentation to parties who have responded to the notice and there shall be no further notice published. Any procurement will be based on an open procedure.
Interested providers will be able to view the tender opportunity via the 'current tenders' list the In-Tend website:
https://in-tendhost.co.uk/scwcsu/aspx/Home
In order to participate in this procurement providers will need to 'express an interest' and register on the system.Interested parties must express an interest by 12 noon 2 March 2018
As of 1 January 2018 there are 3,879 patients registered at either Hatherleigh Medical Centre or Shebbear Practice. The weighted list size is 4,577.1
The provider will receive the GMS price £81.15 per weighted patient in line with other GP contracts locally.
The provider will have to meet GMS core hours, currently 8am to 6.30pm five days per week. During these hours the site will be expected to be open to deliver face to face appointments for patients currently registered with Hatherleigh Medical Centre or Shebbear Practice and/or for patients of the main surgery for whom this would be a convenient alternative. Any changes to opening hours will require NHSE approval and demonstrate that the effect on access will be at least neutral. Changes to hours or services will be subject to patient engagement and consultation which is the responsibility of the contractor.
TUPE will apply to the contract

Additional information: The Services are healthcare services within the meaning and scope of Annex XIV of Directive 2014/24/EU ("the Directive") and Schedule 3 to the Public Contract Regulations 2015 ("the Regulations"), which are not subject to the full regime of the Regulations, but is instead governed by the "Light Touch Regime", (Articles 74 to 76 of the Directive, and Regulations 74 to 76 of the Regulations).
Interested providers will be able to view this opportunity via the 'current tenders' list on in-tend. https://in-tendhost.co.uk/scwcsu/aspx/Home
In order to participate in this procurement, you will need to 'express an interest' and register on the system. On registration, please include at least two contacts to allow for access to the portal in times of absence. 
The Services are healthcare services within the meaning and scope of Annex XIV of Directive 2014/24/EU("the Directive") and Schedule 3 to the Public Contract Regulations 2015 ("the Regulations"). The tendering process will be conducted in accordance with the requirements and flexibilities provided by Articles 74 to 76 of the Directive, and Regulations 74 to 76 of the Regulations. The Authority will run a transparent tender process, treating all bidders equally. For the avoidance of doubt, the Authority will not be bound by the Regulations or the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union or any other regulations or legislation except for the specific arts or circumstances that apply to the procurement of these Services.
Neither the inclusion of a bidder selection stage, nor the use of any language or terms found in the Directive or Regulations, nor the description of the procedure voluntarily adopted by the Authority ("Open", "Restricted", "Competitive Procedure with Negotiation", "Competitive Dialogue" or any other description), nor any other indication, shall be taken to mean that the Authority intends to hold itself bound by the Directive or Regulations, save by the provisions applicable to services coming within the scope of Annex XIV of the Directive / Schedule3of the Regulations. releases/0/tender/title: Identification of Sites for Habitat Creation
releases/0/tender/description:
The MMO has identified, through stakeholder engagement (as part of marine planning) and through internal engagement and analysis that there is a need to increase the amount of evidence in relation to:

a) creating a publicly available, national dataset  showing the type and location of sites with potential to become significant habitats. This dataset would be able to be integrated into existing information systems, to show where these sites may be. This project would look to recommend ways to keep this dataset up to date in a cost-effective and timely fashion
b) using this information and an analysis of existing policy and delivery initiatives to assess what role there may be for marine planning and marine licensing in either safeguarding these sites or advising applicants of their existence, in relation to individual applications.

This has been highlighted as an issue by stakeholders through marine planning stakeholder engagement and independently is something the marine conservation team had identified as a need. The intended result is to try and improve the environmental policy provision in marine plans and contribute more to environmental protection, whilst helping the economy to flourish.

Additional information: 
Please note that Defra procurement uses an E-tendering system for Procurement activities.  This is currently provided by Bravo Solutions.   To access appropriate tendering and contractual documents, please access the E-Tendering portal at https://defra.bravosolution.co.uk", ensuring that your registration includes "Defra".  If you have any problems with this system, please contact Bravo on their telephone helpline number 0800 368 4850 or by emailing them at help@bravosolution.co.uk. "

releases/0/tender/title: GB-Chelmsford: 0592 Tri LEP Energy Strategy
releases/0/tender/description:
The South East Local Enterprise Partnership (SELEP) requires consultancy services for the production of a tri-LEP Energy Strategy and Action Plan.  The provider will work closely with the tri-LEP Project Steering Group and Project Working Group on two integrated work streams - data collation and analysis, and stakeholder engagement and consultation - to produce a comprehensive and robust energy strategy and action plan in line with current best practice, regional needs and government expectations. 
      
      The provider will have the capacity and capability to undertake collation, mapping, analysis and modelling of the energy opportunities across the whole tri-LEP geography, for power, heat and transport.  The provider will underpin this process with thorough stakeholder engagement across the public and private sector to ensure accuracy and ownership for implementation of the strategy and action plan.

releases/0/tender/title: "Breck's last game" - A Short Film
releases/0/tender/description:
AWARD NOTICE

Leicestershire Police wishes to commission an independent film maker to produce a short film (the working title of which is "Breck's Last Game") which will form the centrepiece of a campaign to be launched in Leicestershire (and very probably in other police force areas) in February 2018.
The overall aims of the campaign are to:
•	increase public awareness that teenage boys are just as susceptible to becoming victims of child sexual exploitation and abuse as are teenage girls;
•	encourage greater awareness of the signs that teenage boys may be being abused / exploited; 
•	increase the reporting of offences being committed against teenage boys.
•	prevent such crimes.

releases/0/tender/description:
GreenSquare Group are currently out to tender (quotes) for the supply, servicing and maintenance of commercial lawnmowers. Servicing & maintenance programme for 3 - 5 years.
      
      Suppliers that would like to take part in this tender process are invited to Express Interest upon which they will be given access to the full tender documentation delivery through this e-tendering system.
      
      When the tender documents have been made available suppliers will receive notification via email and the tender documents can be accessed from the My Tenders area of the website and selecting the View Details button of this project.
      
      Expressions of Interest will only be accepted until midnight 27/02/2018 and the deadline for submissions of the tender (quote) will be midnight 28/02/2018. Please note we will require you to upload some additional documents (for example insurances) before you are able to submit your quote and you should allow sufficient time to make your return as late returns will not be permitted
      
      Any questions relating to this tender (quote) should be made via correspondence on the website and can be addressed to the main contact as shown in the details above.

Additional information: Interested parties may Express Interest in this opportunity upon which you will receive electronic documentation.



Delivery Notes

Delivery of mowers to SN15. Full address to be confirmed with the winning bidder.

releases/0/tender/title: Re-roofing of Infants Classroom Block at Oldbury Park Primary School Oldbury Road Worcester Worcestershire WR2 6AA
releases/0/tender/description:
Place Partnership Ltd. on behalf of Worcestershire County Council invite suitable, qualified and experienced Building Contractors to carry out Re-roofing Works to the Infants Classroom Block at Oldbury Park Primary School Oldbury Road Worcester Worcestershire WR2 6AA
      
      It is on this basis that we invite suitable contractors to provide a full turn-key project compliant quotation, to deliver this project within set time scales.
      
      Before tendering, contractors must arrange to carry out a site inspection. 
      
      To arrange access to carry out this inspection contact Steven Wharrad of Place Partnership on 077100 68908
      
      The works are to be carried out and completed between 3rd April 2018 and the 27th April 2018.
      
      Term of Contract JCT Minor Works Building Contract 2016
      
      To register your interest or to download all tender documents please visit the Worcestershire County Council's e-procurement portal at: https://www.in-tendhost.co.uk/worcestershire
      
      All tender documents must be uploaded to the portal by the due date as late returns will not be accepted.
      
      Tenders and supporting documents shall be in English and any contract subsequently entered in to shall be subject to English Law.
      
      Please note that the Supplier is responsible for obtaining all information necessary for the preparation of the tender submission. All cost, expenses and liabilities incurred by the Supplier in connection with the preparation of their submission, the Form of Tender and Pricing Schedule shall be borne by the Supplier.
      
      Worcestershire County Council reserve the right not to award a contract in full or in part.

Additional information: 
To register your interest or to download all tender documents please visit the Worcestershire County Council e-procurement portal at:
https:www.in-tendhost.co.uk/worcestershire
